    "created_at": "2012-03-07T20:06:11Z",
    "updated_at": "2012-03-07T20:06:11Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "also, for the pyplot interface, a new figure is made for every cell - so if you have one cell that does \n`plot(sin(range(10)))` and the next cell does `plot(range(10))` - you'll only get one line in each plot. You'll need to start using the object-oriented interface of matplotlib in order to update the same underlying figure across different cells.\n\nThis just means that you need to keep around references to figure and axes in variables\n"
  },
